<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
    Hardened-runtime entitlements for Roost.app.

    Effective when the bundle is code-signed (ad-hoc or Developer
    ID). bundle.sh signs with the `runtime` option; Phase 8 adds
    Developer ID + notarization on top (#83).

    com.apple.security.device.audio-input
    com.apple.security.device.camera
    com.apple.security.automation.apple-events

    Roost is the TCC *responsible app* for the programs it hosts: when
    a child process in a tab (Claude Code's /voice, ffmpeg, sox, an
    osascript automation) touches the microphone, camera, or sends
    Apple events, macOS attributes the request to Roost, not the
    child. Under the hardened runtime that attribution is *silently
    denied* unless Roost carries the matching resource entitlement —
    no prompt, no Privacy pane entry, no error. These three let those
    requests prompt ("A program running in Roost would like to use the
    microphone") instead of failing silently. The paired purpose
    strings live in Info.plist.template. cf. ghostty and cmux, which
    both carry the same capture set.

    com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation

    Required by the embedded Sparkle.framework (issue #122). Library
    validation insists every linked library be signed by the SAME
    Team ID as the main executable (or be a platform binary). Roost
    ships ad-hoc-signed (no Team ID yet, #83), so the hardened runtime
    would refuse to load the framework and the app would abort at
    launch with a code-signature (LV) kill. This entitlement lifts the
    same-team requirement so the ad-hoc framework loads.

    REMOVE THIS once #83 lands (Developer ID + notarization): when
    Roost and Sparkle.framework are both signed by our Team ID,
    same-team signing satisfies library validation and the entitlement
    is no longer needed (cf. Ghostty, which is team-signed and carries
    no LV-disable). Keeping it past that point needlessly weakens the
    hardened runtime.

    What we still INTENTIONALLY do not need:

    * `cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory` / `cs.allow-jit`
      libghostty-vt is linked as a static archive (its code is part of
      Roost's own signed image), no JIT, no dynamically generated
      machine code at runtime. Add `allow-jit` only if a future
      Ghostty bump introduces a JIT path (e.g. font shaping via SIMD
      codegen).

    * `network.client` / `network.server` Roost does not speak over a
      network socket; the IPC server is UNIX-domain only. (Sparkle's
      update download runs in its own XPC service, which carries its
      own networking; the main app does not need the entitlement.)

    * App Sandbox flags sandboxing the shells Roost spawns would defeat
      the product. cmux makes the same choice.

    * com.apple.security.personal-information.{addressbook,calendars,
      location,photos-library} ghostty carries these; we deliberately
      do NOT. A TCC grant to Roost is inherited by *every* child it
      ever spawns, so the entitlement set is the blast radius. Capture
      devices (mic/camera) light a menu-bar in-use indicator; PIM reads
      have *none* — a buggy or hostile agent could exfiltrate the whole
      address book invisibly. We add a PIM key only if a concrete Roost
      feature needs it (one-line change), not speculatively.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>com.apple.security.device.audio-input</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.device.camera</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.automation.apple-events</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
